remarks.para:
However, if a sub-type is not supported by Hodoku (e.g. the field
), this method will still return 
indicating the "Not supported" state.

target.remarks:
Beginning with C# 7, we can customize the return value type of a  variable
if we implement a parameterless method called GetPinnableReference, returning by
 or . For example, if we hold a fixed buffer
of element type:

class ExampleType
{
    private fixed short _maskList[100];

    public ref readonly short GetPinnableReference() => ref _maskList[0];
}

We can use  statement to define a variable of type *
as the left-value.

var instance = new ExampleType();
fixed (short* ptr = instance)
{
    // Operation here.
}

remarks.para:
This method returns the reference, which means you can use this method as an lvalue.
For example, if you want to use bitwise-or operator to update the value, you can use:

// Update the mask.
short mask = ...;
grid.GetMaskRefAt(0) |= mask;

The expression grid.GetMaskRefAt(0) |= mask is equivalent to
grid.GetMaskRefAt(0) = grid.GetMaskRefAt(0) | mask, and it can be replaced
with the expression grid._values[0] = grid._values[0] | mask,
meaning we update the mask at the first place (i.e. r1c1).

member.remarks:
Please note that the iterator will iterate all masks by reference, which means
you can apply  and  modifier
onto the iteration variable:

foreach (ref readonly short mask in grid)
{
    // Do something.
}

We suggest you use  to achieve same goal if the passing argument is a constant.
For example:

var grid1 = (Grid)"123456789456789123789123456214365897365897214897214365531642978642978531978531642";
var grid2 = (Grid)"987654321654321987321987654896745213745213896213896745579468132468132579132579468";
var grid3 = Grid.Parse(stringCode); // 'stringCode' is a string, not null.

remarks.para:
For example, if you have defined a  deconstruction method Deconstruct
in a , without any return value:

public static void Deconstruct(out string name, out int age)
{
    name = Name;
    age = Age;
}

The following code will be legal.

// Use explicitly typed variables to get a deconstruction.
(string name, int age) = student;

// Or use the type inferring to omit the type of each variable having been deconstructed.
var (name, age) = student;

// Of course, you can also use the invocation to get values.
student.Deconstruct(out string name, out int age);

Deconstruction methods also allow you using deconstruction patterns, like this:

if (student is (name: var name, age: >= 18))
{
    Console.WriteLine(name);
}

